{"name": "pyxlsb", "metadata": {"name": "pyxlsb", "version": "1.0.10", "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 5 - Production/Stable", "License :: OSI Approved :: GNU Lesser General Public License v3 or later (LGPLv3+)", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.5", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.6", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9"], "home_page": "https://github.com/willtrnr/pyxlsb", "license": "LGPLv3+", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": [], "summary": "Excel 2007-2010 Binary Workbook (xlsb) parser", "upload_time": 1665775066}, "documentation": ["---\nsubstitutions:\n  PyPI: |-\n    ```{image} https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/pyxlsb.svg\n    :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pyxlsb\n    ```\n---\n\n# pyxlsb\n\n{{ PyPI }}\n\n`pyxlsb` is an Excel 2007-2010 Binary Workbook (xlsb) parser for\nPython. The library is currently extremely limited, but functional\nenough for basic data extraction.\n\n## Install\n\n```sh\npip install pyxlsb\n```\n\n## Usage\n\nThe module exposes an `open_workbook(name)` method (similar to Xlrd\nand OpenPyXl) for opening XLSB files. The Workbook object representing\nthe file is returned.\n\n```python\nfrom pyxlsb import open_workbook\nwith open_workbook('Book1.xlsb') as wb:\n    # Do stuff with wb\n```\n\nThe Workbook object exposes a `get_sheet(idx)` method for retrieving a\nWorksheet instance.\n\n```python\n# Using the sheet index (1-based)\nwith wb.get_sheet(1) as sheet:\n    # Do stuff with sheet\n\n# Using the sheet name\nwith wb.get_sheet('Sheet1') as sheet:\n    # Do stuff with sheet\n```\n\nTip: A `sheets` property containing the sheet names is available on\nthe Workbook instance.\n\nThe `rows()` method will hand out an iterator to read the worksheet\nrows.\n\n```python\n# You can use .rows(sparse=True) to skip empty rows\nfor row in sheet.rows():\n    print(row)\n# [Cell(r=0, c=0, v='TEXT'), Cell(r=0, c=1, v=42.1337)]\n```\n\nDo note that dates will appear as floats. You must use the\n`convert_date(date)` method from the `pyxlsb` module to turn them\ninto `datetime` instances.\n\n```python\nfrom pyxlsb import convert_date\nprint(convert_date(41235.45578))\n# datetime.datetime(2012, 11, 22, 10, 56, 19)\n```\n"], "modules": [{"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [{"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable", "bases": ["object"], "methods": [{"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.__init__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "fp", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.__enter__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.__exit__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "type", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "value", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "traceback", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.__getitem__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "key", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable._parse", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.get_string", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "idx", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pyxlsb.stringtable.StringTable.close", "asynchronous"